## Coding Standards

{% if "Python" in languages -%}
### Python

- Runtime: Python 3.12+ via pyenv
- Package manager: `uv` (NOT pip, NOT poetry)
- Test runner: `uv run pytest tests/ -v`
- Formatting: ruff format, ruff check --fix
- Type hints: Required on all public functions
- Async: Prefer async/await for I/O operations
- Imports: stdlib → third-party → local, each group separated by blank line
- Naming: snake_case for functions/variables, PascalCase for classes, UPPER_CASE for constants
- Error handling: Specific exceptions, never bare `except:`. Only catch what you can handle.
- DB: asyncpg for PostgreSQL, aiosqlite for SQLite. Always use parameterized queries.
- Patterns: Repository pattern for DB, dependency injection for services, dataclasses/Pydantic for models.
{% endif -%}

{% if "TypeScript" in languages or "JavaScript" in languages -%}
### TypeScript / JavaScript

- Package manager: Check project (npm/pnpm/bun). When ambiguous, check lockfile.
- Formatting: Biome or Prettier (check project config)
- Strict mode always. No `any` unless truly necessary (document why).
- Prefer `interface` over `type` for object shapes.
- Use `const` by default, `let` only when reassignment needed.
{% endif -%}

{% if "SQL" in languages -%}
### SQL

- Always use parameterized queries. Never interpolate user input.
- Use CTEs for complex queries. Name them descriptively.
- Always specify column names in INSERT (never INSERT INTO t VALUES).
{% endif -%}

{% if "Go" in languages -%}
### Go

- Use `go fmt` and `go vet` before committing.
- Error handling: Always check errors. Never use `_` for error returns.
- Prefer table-driven tests.
{% endif -%}

### Git

- Conventional commits: `feat:`, `fix:`, `docs:`, `test:`, `chore:`, `refactor:`
- Commit subjects: ~70 chars max, imperative mood
- Branch naming: `feature/`, `fix/`, `chore/` prefixes
- Never force push to main/master
- Never bypass git hook verification
- Never use `git add -A` — stage specific files only

### Testing

- Write tests alongside implementation, not as afterthought
- Unit tests: Fast, isolated, no external dependencies
- Integration tests: Real database, real services (no mocks for DB)
- Minimum: Test happy path + 1 error path + 1 edge case
- Never modify existing tests to make new code pass — fix the code instead

